A) Old way: doRNG + chunkVector

You bundle trials into chunks first, then give each worker one chunk.

Example chunking:
	•	Chunk 1: 1,2,3,4
	•	Chunk 2: 5,6,7,8
	•	Chunk 3: 9,10,11,12

How it runs:
	•	Worker 1 runs trials 1→2→3→4 (one after another)
	•	Worker 2 runs trials 5→6→7→8
	•	Worker 3 runs trials 9→10→11→12

RNG implication: each worker’s random numbers get used sequentially across all trials in its chunk.

If later you change to 4 workers, the chunking changes, so the order of random numbers per trial can change → results may change unless you’re extremely careful.

⸻

B) New way: future with future.scheduling = 3

Here, future also bundles work, but it does the bundling for you.

scheduling = 3 means:

“Make tasks that contain about 3 trials per task.”

So future creates tasks like:
	•	Task A: trials 1,2,3
	•	Task B: trials 4,5,6
	•	Task C: trials 7,8,9
	•	Task D: trials 10,11,12

Now assign tasks to 3 workers:
	•	Worker 1 gets Task A (1,2,3)
	•	Worker 2 gets Task B (4,5,6)
	•	Worker 3 gets Task C (7,8,9)
	•	when any worker finishes, the remaining Task D (10,11,12) is given to whoever becomes free first.

So workers do multiple tasks over time, but each task is a bundle of 3 trials.

RNG implication with future.seed=TRUE:
	•	each task gets its own reproducible random stream.
	•	but the three trials inside the same task share that task’s stream.
	•	if the task grouping changes (different workers / different scheduling / load balancing), the RNG usage per trial can shift.

So compared to scheduling=1:
	•	scheduling=3 is faster (fewer tasks)
	•	but slightly less “exactly reproducible across different parallel setups”
